#: ../../source/manual/how-tos/nginx_waf.rst:57
msgid ""
"WAF rules are used to trigger an action if a condition evaluates to true "
"or false (negated). The usual use case is increasing a score which can be"
" checked afterwards, but a rule can for example also block instantly (the"
" plugin only supports a score). WAF rules are grouped to a WAF policy, "
"which then can evaluate the aggregated score."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manual/how-tos/nginx_waf.rst:61
msgid ""
"The description will be shown in the GUI and the Message will appear in "
"the log. Negate will switch the condition form \"if\" to \"unless\". The "
"ID must be unique. You should use a scheme like 1000 to 2000 are SQL "
"injection or similar because that improves log evaluation if needed (for "
"example you could create pie charts because you can group by the id "
"range)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manual/how-tos/nginx_waf.rst:63
msgid ""
"The next section describes the rule type and the match. You can scan the "
"match value like `truncate` (an SQL keyword to delete the content of the "
"table) in different places in the HTTP request. Mostly all of them can be"
" checked or as an alternative, you can use a name so it will only match a"
" specific header for example. Please note that not all of them are "
"compatible with each other so please consult the NAXSI docs."
msgstr ""

